snippet.textDisplay:
Weird ppl who clicked dislike. This video is already getting crazy views so could just be what happens with anything viral. 1 dislike for every 7 likes. But as usual, great breakdown and showing a couple of things I didn't see during the fight. The majority of people don't understand the technical aspects of mma striking. And I think you're right about shoulder strikes in the clinch being used by other fighters now, but it only seems to be that effective for the shorter fighter and also being delivered with good technique. As you pointed the out, Cowboy wasn't expecting them and before he knew it he had been cracked 3 times with a 4th landing on the nose before he was able to break and retreat. The 1st one looks like the one that did damage around the eye. I hope someone can get Donald to have his nose checked out, just in case there's something he can do to repair it better moving forward. Because he's taken some damage over the years and in the last 3 especially, his nose has been cracked in all of them if I'm not mistaken.
Either way, I'm happy he wasn't put out cold and still able to talk and smile a bit afterward. I love both of these fighters and with my heart wanted a good fight, but my head was saying it's going to be a short night for Donald.
Now the 2020 season kicks off in a big way for Conor. Keep him active. Fuk ur LW title shot, Dana. That's too long to wait. I thought the Conor who fought Nate at 170 was just a bit too small for Jorge, but now he's looking thicker and stronger. Ppl forget how big Conor's hands are. That comes into play with the hand fighting for control on the cage and in other mma grappling aspects. I really am interested in seeing that fight now.

snippet.textDisplay: Guys, not all, but many of these fights are so subtly fixed. McGregor is the UFC's boy. Cerrone's had over 50 pro fights and he loses in a minute or two, particularly in that fashion? Come on... Keep your eyes open. The media spins the narrative before the fight to plant the subliminal seed in the audience's mind: "McGregor starts fast"; "Cerrone starts slow" (Remember: the bulk of the media comes from outlets that have corporate partnerships with the UFC (ESPN, etc.)). The UFC probably has very specific contracts with these fighters per fight that limits them - what they can literally physically do - in the fight, in order to ensure the fight goes a certain way.... Just sayin'.
